This article is part of my SOLID Principles in Angular series, where I break down each SOLID principle from an Angular engineer’s perspective using practical examples and real-world Angular scenarios.
In this article, we’ll focus on the Dependency Inversion Principle (DIP).
Like the other SOLID principles, this one is simple to understand in theory, but applying it consistently in real-world applications requires experience and thoughtful design.
When used correctly, DIP helps us build Angular applications that are easier to maintain, scale, and evolve as business requirements grow. It’s time to break it down and see how it applies to modern Angular development.
What does the Dependency Inversion Principle say?
High-level modules should not depend on low-level modules. Both should depend on abstractions.
This is arguably one of the most important SOLID principles in Angular. In fact, Angular’s entire dependency injection system is heavily built around this idea. In simple words, the DI says:
Depend on abstractions, not concrete implementations.
This principle helps reduce coupling between different parts of an application. Why does that matter? Tightly coupled systems are difficult to maintain, test, scale, and extend. Let’s look at a simple example.
class UserComponent {
service = new UserService();
}This creates a problem because theUserComponent is directly creating its own dependency, which means the component is tightly coupled to UserService. Why is that bad? If the implementation changes, the component may need to change too. Angular Improves This with Dependency Injection. This is where Angular shines. Instead of manually creating dependencies, Angular injects them as below code:
constructor(private userService: UserService) {}This is already better because the component no longer creates the service itself, and Angular handles that responsibility.
This gives us cleaner code, easier testing, and better maintainability, but we can improve even further.
Better with Abstraction
The real power of DIP comes from depending on abstractions instead of concrete implementations. see the below code:
interface Logger {
log(message: string): void;
}As you can see, now our component depends on a contract, not a specific implementation, which is a major improvement.
Logging Example
Without DI:
class UserComponent {
logger = new ConsoleLogger(); save() {
this.logger.log('saved');
}
}
This works fine, but there’s a problem. Let’s see what happens if later we want to replace ConsoleLogger with:

• API logger

• file logger

• cloud logger
Obviously, we must modify the component that violates DIP.
Better Design with DI + Abstraction
First, define abstraction.
interface Logger {
log(message: string): void;
}Now create implementations.
@Injectable()
class ConsoleLogger implements Logger {
log(message: string) {
console.log(message);
}
}@Injectable()
class ApiLogger implements Logger {
log(message: string) {
// send logs to backend
}
}
Now inject dependency.
@Component({})
class UserComponent {
constructor(private logger: Logger) {} save() {
this.logger.log('saved');
}
}
The component no longer cares about implementation details. It only cares that the injected dependency supports:
log()That’s exactly what DIP encourages.
Provider Configuration
Angular decides which implementation to provide.
Development:
{ provide: Logger, useClass: ConsoleLogger }Production:
{ provide: Logger, useClass: ApiLogger }Notice something important: The component never changes, only configuration changes. That gives us tremendous flexibility.
Real Angular Example: InjectionToken
There’s one important Angular-specific detail. Interfaces do not exist at runtime in TypeScript; because of that, Angular often uses InjectionToken. let’s explore it via an example:
export interface Logger {
log(message: string): void;
}export const LOGGER = new InjectionToken<Logger>('LOGGER');Provider:
providers: [
{ provide: LOGGER, useClass: ConsoleLogger }
]Injection:
constructor(@Inject(LOGGER) private logger: Logger) {}This is a very common Angular pattern in real-world applications. Senior Angular engineers should be comfortable with it.
Which SOLID Principles Matter Most in Angular?
I get asked this quite often. If I had to choose the most impactful SOLID principles in Angular, I’d pick SRP, DIP, and OCP. Why?
SRP keeps components focused on UI responsibilities while business logic lives in services.
DIP is at the heart of Angular’s dependency injection system.
OCP helps teams build systems that evolve safely as business requirements grow.
These three principles heavily influence how scalable your Angular architecture becomes.
Final Thoughts
SOLID principles are not just academic theory; they solve real engineering problems, especially in Angular applications. They help us build systems that are scalable, maintainable, testable, and easier to evolve, but just like OOP, SOLID is not the ultimate goal; a good architecture is the final goal.
If you enjoyed this article and want to dive deeper into Angular architecture, you might also be interested in my article on Object-Oriented Programming in Angular.
